<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPOTLIGHT : CLASSICAL MUSIC; 
</P>
<P>
OPERA, SYMPHONY CHIEFS HAVE HIGH HOPES FOR '90S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNETH HERMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the 1990s, San Diego's classical music institutions hope to atone for the 
sins of the last decade. 
</P>
<P>
At Symphony Hall, incoming music director Yoav Talmi will undertake the musical 
reconstruction of an orchestra that has been without a music director for three 
years, while executive director Wesley Brustad and board members look for a 
generous donor whose "naming gift" will absorb half of the lingering $4-million 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
Ian Campbell, having put San Diego Opera's house in fiscal order, is more 
concerned with righting the sins of omission (mainly in programming) over the 
last decade. 
</P>
<P>
"Our immediate challenge is to include 20th-Century repertory in our seasons as 
a matter of course," said Campbell, the opera's general director. "Not that the 
company hasn't done this repertory in the past, but we've had no regular diet 
to allow our audiences to grow into newer operas. As we enter the last decade 
of the century, we need to do a gentle catch-up." 
</P>
<P>
Not only is Campbell promising 20th-Century opera in every season -- and he 
insisted that he means operas more adventuresome than late Puccini and Richard 
Strauss -- he intends to restore American opera to the company's offerings at 
least every other year. 
</P>
<P>
"We will have two 20th-Century operas in 1991, including (American composer) 
Carlisle Floyd's 'The Passion of Jonathan Wade,' with Floyd directing the 
production." Less well-known than Floyd's other operas -- "Susannah" and "Of 
Mice and Men" are his calling cards -- "The Passion of Jonathan Wade" is echt 
Americana, set in South Carolina immediately after the Civil War. Commissioned 
by New York City Opera, the opera was first performed in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
As part of a cautious expansion of the company's season at Civic Theatre, 
Campbell sees a five-opera season for the first half of the 1990s and a 
six-opera season by the second half of the decade. 
</P>
<P>
"I see the market place more complex in the 1990s, and we have to be practical 
about expanding," Campbell explained. He noted, however, that the success of 
"Cats," "Les Miserables," and "Phantom of the Opera" on the popular 
contemporary music stage could be beneficial for traditional opera. 
</P>
<P>
"These shows are actually opera in their form, because they are sung all the 
way through with little or no dialogue. They could act as a bridge for people 
who have previously avoided opera and encourage them to try something like 
"Madama Butterfly." 
</P>
<P>
Campbell, recently returned from a European scouting mission, had no news to 
report about up-and-coming tenor superstars to add to the performances. He did, 
however, manage to sign the promising young German baritone Hans Peter 
Blochwitz to sing a recital here in October, 1990, which will mark his American 
recital debut. 
</P>
<P>
Other singers Campbell promises in San Diego Opera productions during the 1990s 
include familiar names such as Carol Vaness, Hakan Hagegard, Ashley Putnam and 
Diana Soviero. Among the younger singers, he has signed American tenors Richard 
Leech and Gary Lakes, as well as baritone Thomas Hampson. 
</P>
<P>
"In the coming decade, we will be hiring fewer foreign singers in major roles 
because a new crop of American singers is just now coming into its own." 
</P>
<P>
Campbell also indicated that his company might dabble in the Gilbert and 
Sullivan repertory or include an occasional classic American musical in its 
lineup, although not without first talking with local companies who specialize 
in these areas to ensure that the opera company will undertake complementary 
offerings. He is also keeping his eye on the vacant -- and currently unrestored 
-- Balboa Theater as a potential venue for chamber opera, an alternative season 
geared to appeal to a new audience. 
</P>
<P>
When Campbell pulls out his wish list, the Australian native dreams of a 
dramatic new opera complex on the San Diego harbor, much like the 
architecturally stunning opera house in Sydney. Although with a probable price 
tag of $150 million, Campbell's company is not about to undertake a building 
fund. 
</P>
<P>
For the decade's close, Campbell envisions the company commissioning an opera 
to herald the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
"For a new century, we need to premiere a new opera. San Diego Opera hasn't 
commissioned an opera since Menotti's 'La Loca' (1979). We need to do it as a 
statement." 
</P>
<P>
For the San Diego Symphony, Brustad has concrete plans for the next three to 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
"First of all, the orchestra will be recording for first time ever on a major 
label. When we start seeing the records in stores, it won't be a big money 
thing, but it will be a significant achievement for the musicians," Brustad 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, Yoav (Talmi) and I are committed to the touring of the orchestra, 
not because we think that we are the Philadelphia Orchestra, but for the 
artistic development of the orchestra's ensemble by playing in other venues in 
different cities. Touring also brings back good will here to the city. If 
people here in town read in an out-of-town newspaper, 'These guys played like 
angels,' then they're more than just the hometown boys." 
</P>
<P>
Concerning changes in the orchestra's programming, the ball is now in Talmi's 
court. 
</P>
<P>
"He has a wide repertory," Brustad noted, "but I'm curious to see how it will 
play in the first couple of years. It's different to talk about varied 
programming and then get into the music director's chair, where you're the one 
who's going to be shot at. You tend to tighten up a little bit. It will be 
interesting for me to see how he maneuvers his way through. I know that he does 
not want to isolate contemporary music into a single series by itself, 
however." 
</P>
<P>
Brustad's biggest hope for the decade is to move from Hospitality Point on 
Mission Bay into a new home for the symphony's summer concerts. 
</P>
<P>
"What we've got out there is cute and nice, but it's a little temporary. After 
eight years, we need something more substantial, a larger, permanent venue on 
the water that will allow us to move toward more of a Hollywood Bowl venue and 
program." 
</P>
<P>
According to Brustad, he is not simply empire building. This type of summer 
facility with income-producing events augmenting the pops programs is essential 
for the orchestra's future economic stability. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't see this town supporting its orchestra like they do in Boston. It's 
simple as the weather. It's just too nice to live here, which is why the summer 
pops works so beautifully -- it's outdoors. You don't fight the weather; you're 
part of it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Ian Campbell Los Angeles Times; Photo, Wesley Brustad 
</P>
