CAR BOMB KILLS ULSTER CABBIE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BELFAST, Northern Ireland 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A car bomb exploded today in east Belfast, killing a cabbie who was driving his 
daughter to school, police said. 
</P>
<P>
The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old girl was wounded in the attack, the Royal Ulster Constabulary 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Harry Dickey, 37, and his daughter became the first victims of 1990 of Northern 
Ireland's 20-year-old political and sectarian violence. They were heading to 
the daughter's school when the bomb exploded and the car crashed into a lamp 
post, a police spokesman said. 
</P>
