<HEADLINE>
<P>
RACING YACHT RUNS INTO WHALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WELLINGTON, New Zealand 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
French yacht Charles Jourdan sailed into a whale today and sustained 
substantial damage, organizers of the Whitbread round-the-world ocean race 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The yacht, in seventh place at the time of the collision, is to continue the 
third leg of the race from Fremantle, Australia, to Auckland. 
</P>
<P>
Race officials in Auckland said skipper Max-Philippe Couteau had radioed to say 
the French yacht hit the whale early this afternoon. He said the planking on 
the starboard side had been damaged and there was a gash 6 feet long and 1 foot 
wide. 
</P>
<P>
"We are attempting to make temporary repairs at sea," Couteau told officials. 
"If possible and weather permitting, we will continue our route towards 
Auckland." 
</P>
<P>
New Zealand yachts Steinlager II and Fisher and Paykel continued to lead the 
23-yacht fleet late today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
